# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mandana-seyfeddinipur
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] In its earliest usage, *alma mater* was an honorific title for various mother goddesses, especially Ceres or Cybele.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] Later, in Catholicism, it became a title for Mary, mother of Jesus.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] By the early 17th century, the nursing mother became an allegory for universities.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] Used by many schools in Europe and North America, it has special association with the University of Bologna, whose motto *Alma Mater Studiorum* ("nurturing mother of studies") emphasizes its role in originating the modern university.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] Several university campuses in North America display artistic representations of *Alma Mater*, depicted as a robed woman wearing a laurel wreath crown.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] The earliest and of these is the bronze *Alma Mater* statue at Columbia University, designed in 1901 by Daniel Chester French.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] In the US the term *alma mater* is often used to describe a school song.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] Although *alma* (nourishing) was a common epithet for Ceres, Cybele, Venus, and other mother goddesses, it was not frequently used in conjunction with *mater* in classical Latin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] After the fall of Rome, the term was used in Christian liturgy to describe Jesus' mother, Mary.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] "Alma Redemptoris Mater" is a well-known eleventh century antiphon devoted to Mary.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] The earliest documented use of the term to refer to a university is in 1600, when the University of Cambridge printer, John Legate, began using an emblem for the university press.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] The first-known appearance of the device is in William Perkins', *A Golden Chain*, a book first printed by Legate in 1600.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] On the title-page, the Latin phrase *Alma Mater Cantabrigia* ("nourishing mother Cambridge") is inscribed on a pedestal bearing a lactating woman wearing a mural crown.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] In reference works of English etymology, often the first university-related usage is cited as 1710, when an academic mother figure is mentioned in a remembrance of Henry More by Richard Ward.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] Many historic European universities have adopted *Alma Mater* as part of the Latin translation of their official name.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] The Latin name of the University of Bologna, *Alma Mater Studiorum* (nourishing mother of studies), refers to its status as the oldest continuously operating university in the world.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] At other European universities, such as the Alma Mater Lipsiensis in Leipzig, Germany, or Alma Mater Jagiellonica, Poland, the title emphasizes historic ties to a founding city or dynasty.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] The Alma Mater Europaea in Salzburg, Austria, an international university founded by the European Academy of Sciences and Arts in 2010, uses the term as its official name.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] In the United States, the College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia, has been called the "Alma Mater of the Nation" because of its ties to the founding of the country.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] At Queen's University in Kingston, Ontario, and the University of British Columbia in Vancouver, British Columbia, the main student government is known as the Alma Mater Society.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] Sculptures of *Alma Mater* are found on several North American university campuses.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] In 1901, to commemorate the opening of the Low Library, Columbia University commissioned Daniel Chester French to design a bronze statue for the library's steps.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] French chose the *Alma Mater* to allegorically embody the university without depicting its founder, King George II.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] A similar sculpture, cast in 1919 by Mario Korbel, sits on the main entrance steps at the University of Havana.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] Other tributes to *Alma Mater* include Lorado Taft's *1929 sculpture* at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign and Cyrus Dallin's 1925 sculpture at the Mary Institute in 1925, commissioned by Washington University supporters.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/alma-mater] An altarpiece mural in Yale University's Sterling Memorial Library, painted in 1932 by Eugene Savage, depicts the *Alma Mater* as a bearer of light and truth, standing in the midst of figures representing the arts and sciences.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The **Berlin-Brandenburg Academy of Sciences and Humanities** (German: *Berlin-Brandenburgische Akademie der Wissenschaften*), abbreviated **BBAW**, is the official academic society for the natural sciences and humanities for the German states of Berlin and Brandenburg.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Housed in three locations in and around Berlin, Germany, the BBAW is the largest non-university humanities research institute in the region.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The BBAW was constituted in 1992 by formal treaty between the governments of Berlin and Brandenburg on the basis of several older academies, including the historic Prussian Academy of Sciences from 1700 and East Germany's Academy of Sciences of the German Democratic Republic from 1946.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] By this tradition, past members include the Brothers Grimm, Wilhelm and Alexander von Humboldt, Lise Meitner, Theodor Mommsen, Albert Einstein, and Max Planck.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Today the BBAW operates as a public law corporation (German: *Körperschaft des öffentlichen Rechts*) in cooperation with the German National Academy of Sciences, and has over 300 fellows and 250 additional staff members.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Its elected scientific membership has included 78 Nobel laureates.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The BBAW operates several subsidiary research centers.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Projects include compiling large dictionaries; editing texts from ancient, medieval, and modern history; and editing the classical literature from diverse fields.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The roots of the BBAW can be traced to the Society of Sciences of the Elector of Brandenburg (German: *Kurfürstlich Brandenburgische Sozietät der Wissenschaften*), founded in 1700 by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz under the patronage of Frederick I of Prussia.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The institution was created on the principle of uniting the natural sciences and the humanities, making it a prototype for other academies across Europe.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The rise of the field of physics can be genealogically traced to this period of the Academy, as well as modern European mathematics.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Under Frederick the Great, an enthusiastic patron, the Academy rose to even wider significance.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] In 1752 it merged with the *Nouvelle Société Littéraire* to form the *Royal Academy of Sciences* (German: *Königliche Akademie der Wissenschaften*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The new Academy attracted prominent scientists and philosophers, including Immanuel Kant, who were able publish writings which would have been censored elsewhere in Europe.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] While it was an important center in the Age of Enlightenment, due to its royal patronage the Academy did not enjoy complete freedom.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Political writings in its *Proceedings* throughout the 18th century argued the merits of monarchies over republics, warned against the French Revolution, and defended Prussia against accusations that it was despotic.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Around 1812 the academy was officially renamed *Royal Prussian Academy of Sciences*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The von Humboldt brothers reorganized the Academy along more open lines.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Prominent critical thinkers such as Theodor Mommsen, Friedrich Wilhelm Joseph Schelling, Friedrich Schleiermacher were all active members for many decades.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] With the collapse of the German monarchy in 1918, the Royal Academy was renamed the Prussian Academy of Sciences (German: *Preußische Akademie der Wissenschaften*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] During this period it rose to international fame and its members included top academics in their fields such as Albert Einstein, Max Planck, Hermann Diels, and Ernst Bloch.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] During the Nazi period, as with all institutions across Germany, the Academy became subject to the "Law for the Restoration of the Professional Civil Service." As a result, Jewish employees and political opponents were expelled.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Albert Einstein resigned in 1933 before he could be expelled and Max Planck, the Academy's president, was coerced to publicly support nationalist socialism.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] However, despite initial resistance, over time the Academy and many of its scientists became willing tools of the Nazis.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] New statutes in 1938 reorganized the Academy according to the Führer principle, causing Planck to resign his presidency in protest.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The mathematician Theodor Vahlen, proponent of the anti-Semitic *Deutsche Mathematik* movement, was appointed provisionally president by the Reich Ministry of Education.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] In 1939 Vahlen was reconfirmed by the Ministry as acting President, but not elected by the Plenum of the Academy.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Vahlen resigned in 1943 and withdrew to Prague.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] A presidential election in accordance with the statutes had still not taken place by the end of the war.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] By war's end the Academy's reputation was damaged and many of its prominent scientists were stigmatized.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] During the war academy members had still continued their monthly meetings despite bombing of Berlin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] However, many members, especially those of the natural sciences, had left Berlin and moved to the western parts of Germany.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Negotiations of the Academy with the SMAD were successful.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] It was re-established upon the SMAD Order No.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] 187 of July 1, 1946, Leibniz's 300th birthday under a new name with a new structure and role: the Academy was to become the most eminent scientific institution in Germany and for all parts of Germany.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Institutes were added to the Academy and new ones founded.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Re-opened by the Russians in 1946 with the new name German Academy of Sciences at Berlin (German: *Deutsche Akademie der Wissenschaften zu Berlin*), in 1949 it moved to the former Prussian Maritime Trade Company building on the Gendarmenmarkt.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The number of members in additional more applied classes was increased from 70 to 120 and the number of staff members from 130 (1946) to 1,500 (1951).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] In 1972 the Academy was renamed the Academy of Sciences of the German Democratic Republic (German: *Akademie der Wissenschaften der DDR*) or *AdW*, by which time it had over 400 members and 24,000 employees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The society of scholars with about 130 ordinary members and the research institutes existed side by side.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The about 93 institutes of the academy were merged into 43 central and other institutes.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] 1969 the function "as a bridge to West-Germany" was ended and all members not being citizens of the GDR became non-voting external members.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] After German reunification the AdW was dissolved in December 1991 as part of the German Unification Treaty of October 3, 1991 due to its controversial role in support of the East German regime.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] In August 1992, the BBAW was constituted by an interstate treaty between the landtags of Berlin and Brandenburg using the original model of the old Prussian Academy.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] According to the treaty the society of the members of the AdW was separated from the rest of the academy.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Institutes of the Academy were evaluated and in part taken over by other institutions, in part dissolved.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Buildings, traditional projects, archives and libraries were continued by the BBAW.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Today its headquarters are located at the former AdW building, with special projects conducted at the old Prussian Academy on the Unter den Linden.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The academy sponsors a variety of interdisciplinary, long-term and externally funded projects.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] These include large German and foreign-language dictionaries; historical-critical publications of ancient, medieval, and modern texts; and editing and interpreting the classical literature by scholars from diverse academic fields.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The Academy has established a number of research centres over time, including centres for basic research, language and history.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Each seeks to pool expertise from various fields with the goal of improving cooperation between university and non-university institutions and stimulating regional and international research innovation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Funding for the Academy comes primarily from the states of Berlin and Brandenburg, with a significant portion of its research supported by the federal and state governments of Germany.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The Salon Sophie Charlotte is a public evening event organized by the BBAW bringing together leading academics and the general public.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Being selected as an academic panelist or speaker is considered highly prestigious.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The number of visitors increased over the years to up to 3000 visitors (2017) including academics, public intellectuals and politicians such as Chancellor Angela Merkel.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Eponym of the salon is Sophia Charlotte of Hanover (1668–1705), Queen consort in Prussia as wife of King Frederick I., who initiated, together with Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, the founding of the scientific academy in Berlin in 1700.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] On her estate Lietzow (Charlottenburg) near Berlin maintained Sophie Charlotte, who had a great passion for philosophy, free-spirited salons, which formed a counter-world to strict Prussia etiquette as a social meeting place for discussions, readings or musical events.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] The event takes place in BBAW's academy building at Berlin's Gendarmenmarkt.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Every year it is organized with a different thematic focus.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/berlin-brandenburg-academy-of-sciences-and-humanities] Today the BBAW's publications appear in a wide variety of established journals, as well as its own publications such as *Jahrbuch*, *Berichte und Abhandlungen*, *Debatten* and the journal *Gegenworte*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctoral-advisor] Students generally choose advisors based on their areas of interest within their discipline, their desire to work closely with particular graduate faculty, and the willingness and availability of those faculty to work with them.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctoral-advisor] In some countries, the student's advisor is the chair of the dissertation committee or the examination committee.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctoral-advisor] In some cases, though, the person who serves those roles may be different from the faculty member who has most closely advised the student.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctoral-advisor] For instance, in the Dutch academic system, only full professors (*hoogleraren*) and associate professors (since 2017) have the "ius promovendi", the right to chair doctoral examinations.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctoral-advisor] Students who have been advised by lower-ranked faculty members will have a full or associate professor as their official advisor (or *promotor*) and their actual advisor as *co-promotor*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctoral-advisor] In other countries, such as Spain, the doctoral advisor has the role of a mentor, but is not allowed to form part of the examination committee.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctoral-advisor] This is a body of five experts independently selected by the rectorate among ten candidates proposed by the university's department.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctoral-advisor] An academic genealogy may be traced based on the student's doctoral advisors, going up and down the lines of academic "descent" in a manner analogous to a traditional genealogy.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] A **doctorate** (from Latin *doctor*, meaning "teacher") or **doctoral degree** is a postgraduate academic degree awarded by universities and some other educational institutions, derived from the ancient formalism *licentia docendi* ("licence to teach").
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In most countries, a research degree qualifies the holder to teach at university level in the degree's field or work in a specific profession.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] There are a number of doctoral degrees; the most common is the Doctor of Philosophy (PhD), awarded in many different fields, ranging from the humanities to scientific disciplines.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Many universities also award honorary doctorates to individuals deemed worthy of special recognition, either for scholarly work or other contributions to the university or society.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The term *doctor* derives from Latin, meaning "teacher" or "instructor".
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The doctorate (Latin: *doctoratus*) appeared in medieval Europe as a license to teach Latin (*licentia docendi*) at a university.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Its roots can be traced to the early church in which the term *doctor* referred to the Apostles, Church Fathers, and other Christian authorities who taught and interpreted the Bible.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The right to grant a *licentia docendi* (i.e. the doctorate) was originally reserved to the Catholic Church, which required the applicant to pass a test, take an oath of allegiance, and pay a fee.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The Third Council of the Lateran of 1179 guaranteed access—at that time essentially free of charge—to all able applicants.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] This right remained a bone of contention between the church authorities and the universities, slowly distancing themselves from the Church.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In 1213 the right was granted by the pope to the University of Paris, where it became a universal license to teach (*licentia ubique docendi*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] However, while the *licentia* continued to hold a higher prestige than the bachelor's degree (*baccalaureus*), the latter was ultimately reduced to an intermediate step to the master's degree (*magister*) and doctorate, both of which now became the accepted teaching qualifications.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] According to Keith Allan Noble (1994), the first doctoral degree was awarded in medieval Paris around 1150 by the University of Paris.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] George Makdisi theorizes that the *ijazah* issued in early Islamic madrasahs was the origin of the doctorate later issued in medieval European universities.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Alfred Guillaume and Syed Farid al-Attas agree that there is a resemblance between the *ijazah* and the *licentia docendi*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] However, Toby Huff and others reject Makdisi's theory.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Stewart notes a difference in the granting authority (individual professor for the *ijazah* and a corporate entity in the case of the university doctorate).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The doctorate of philosophy developed in Germany in the 17th century (likely c.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The term "philosophy" does not refer here to the field or academic discipline of philosophy; it is used in a broader sense under its original Greek meaning of "love of wisdom".
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In most of Europe, all fields (history, philosophy, social sciences, mathematics, and natural philosophy/natural sciences) were traditionally known as philosophy, and in Germany and elsewhere in Europe the basic faculty of liberal arts was known as the "faculty of philosophy".
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The Doctorate of Philosophy adheres to this historic convention, even though most degrees are not for the study of philosophy itself.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Chris Park explains that it was not until formal education and degree programs were standardized in the early 19th century that the Doctorate of Philosophy was reintroduced in Germany (in what would become the Humboldt University of Berlin) as a research degree, abbreviated as Dr. phil.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] (similar to Ph.D. in Anglo-American countries).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] University doctoral training was a form of apprenticeship to a guild.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The traditional term of study before new teachers were admitted to the guild of "Masters of Arts" was seven years, matching the apprenticeship term for other occupations.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Originally the terms "master" and "doctor" were synonymous, but over time, the doctorate came to be regarded as a higher qualification than the master's degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] University degrees, including doctorates, were originally restricted to men.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The use and meaning of the doctorate have changed over time and are subject to regional variations.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] For instance, until the early 20th century, few academic staff or professors in English-speaking universities held doctorates, except for very senior scholars and those in holy orders.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] After that time, the German practice of requiring lecturers to have completed a research doctorate spread.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Universities' shift to research-oriented education (based upon the scientific method, inquiry, and observation) increased the doctorate's importance.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Today, a research doctorate (PhD) or its equivalent (as defined in the US by the NSF) is generally a prerequisite for an academic career.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] However, many recipients do not work in academia.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Professional doctorates developed in the United States from the 19th century onward.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The first professional doctorate offered in the United States was the MD at Kings College (now Columbia University) after the medical school's founding in 1767.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] However, this was a professional doctorate in the modern American sense.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] It was awarded for further study after the qualifying Bachelor of Medicine (MB) rather than a qualifying degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The MD became the standard first degree in medicine in the US during the 19th century, but as a three-year undergraduate degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] It did not become established as a graduate degree until 1930.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] As the standard qualifying degree in medicine, the MD gave that profession the ability (through the American Medical Association, established in 1847 for this purpose) to set and raise standards for entry into professional practice.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In the shape of the German-style PhD, the modern research degree was first awarded in the US in 1861, at Yale University.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] This differed from the MD in that the latter was a vocational "professional degree" that trained students to apply or practice knowledge rather than generate it, similar to other students in vocational schools or institutes.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In the UK, research doctorates initially took higher doctorates in Science and Letters, first introduced at Durham University in 1882.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The PhD spread to the UK from the US via Canada and was instituted at all British universities from 1917.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The first (titled a DPhil) was awarded at the University of Oxford.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Following the MD, the next professional doctorate in the US, the Juris Doctor (JD), was established by the University of Chicago in 1902.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] However, it took a long time to be accepted, not replacing the Bachelor of Laws (LLB) until the 1960s, by which time the LLB was generally taken as a graduate degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Notably, the JD and LLB curriculum were identical, with the degree being renamed as a doctorate, and it (like the MD) was not equivalent to the PhD, raising criticism that it was "not a 'true Doctorate'".
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] When professional doctorates were established in the UK in the late 1980s and early 1990s, they did not follow the US model.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Still, they were set up as research degrees at the same level as PhDs but with some taught components and a professional focus for research work.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Now usually called higher doctorates in the United Kingdom, the older-style doctorates take much longer to complete since candidates must show themselves to be leading experts in their subjects.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] These doctorates are less common than the PhD in some countries and are often awarded *honoris causa*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] A degree beyond a doctorate, the habilitation is used for academic recruitment purposes in several countries within the EU.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Especially in Germany, it can be a requirement for appointment as a *Privatdozent* or professor.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The habilitation requires the candidate to either produce a second, generally longer thesis or a portfolio of research publications.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The habilitation aims to demonstrate independent and thorough research, experience in teaching and lecturing, and, more recently, the ability to generate supportive funding.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Since the Middle Ages, the number and types of doctorates awarded by universities have proliferated throughout the world.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Practice varies from one country to another.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] While a doctorate usually entitles a person to be addressed as "doctor", the use of the title varies widely depending on the type and the associated occupation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Research doctorates are awarded in recognition of publishable academic research, at least in principle, in a peer-reviewed academic journal.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The best-known research degree in the English-speaking world is the Doctor of Philosophy (abbreviated PhD or, at a small number of British universities, DPhil) awarded in many countries throughout the world.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In the US, for instance, although the most typical research doctorate is the PhD, accounting for about 98% of the research doctorates awarded, there are more than 15 other types of research doctorates.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The UK Doctor of Medicine (MD or MD (Res)) and Doctor of Dental Surgery (DDS) are research doctorates.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The Doctor of Theology (ThD or DTh), Doctor of Practical Theology (DPT) and the Doctor of Sacred Theology (STD, or DSTh) are research doctorates in theology.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Criteria for research doctorates vary but typically require completion of a substantial body of original research, which may be presented as a single thesis or dissertation, or as a portfolio of shorter project reports (thesis by publication).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Certain doctoral programs employ alternative assessment models, in which the degree is awarded based on coursework, examinations, or peer-reviewed publications rather than a single monographic dissertation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The submitted dissertation is assessed by a committee of, typically, internal, and external examiners.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] It is then typically defended by the candidate during an oral examination (called *viva (voce)* in the UK and India) by the committee, which then awards the degree unconditionally, awards the degree conditionally (ranging from corrections in grammar to additional research), or denies the degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Candidates may also be required to complete graduate-level courses in their field and study research methodology.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Criteria for admission to doctoral programs vary.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Students may be admitted with a bachelor's degree in the US and the UK.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] However, elsewhere, (e.g., in Finland and many other European countries), a master's degree is required.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The time required to complete a research doctorate varies from three years, excluding undergraduate study, to six years or more.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Licentiate degrees vary widely in their meaning, and in a few countries are doctoral-level qualifications.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Sweden awards the licentiate degree as a two-year qualification at the doctoral level and the doctoral degree (PhD) as a four-year qualification.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Sweden originally abolished the Licentiate in 1969 but reintroduced it in response to demands from business.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Finland also has a two-year doctoral level licentiate degree, similar to Sweden's.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Outside of Scandinavia, the licentiate is usually a lower-level qualification.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In Belgium, the licentiate was the basic university degree prior to the Bologna Process and was equivalent to a bachelor's degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In France and other countries, it is the bachelor's-level qualification in the Bologna process.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In the Pontifical system, the Licentiate in Sacred Theology (STL) is equivalent to an advanced master's degree, or the post-master's coursework required in preparation for a doctorate (i.e. similar in level to the Swedish/Finnish licentiate degree).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] While other licences (such as the Licence in Canon Law) are at the level of master's degrees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] A higher tier of research doctorates may be awarded based on a formally submitted portfolio of published research of an exceptionally high standard.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Countries in the region of Scandinavia offer a higher research doctorate like the *Doctor Medicinae* (*Dr.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The habilitation teaching qualification (*facultas docendi* or "faculty to teach") under a university procedure with a thesis and an exam is commonly regarded as belonging to this category in Germany, Austria, France, Liechtenstein, Switzerland, Poland, etc.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The degree developed in Germany in the 19th century "when holding a doctorate seemed no longer sufficient to guarantee a proficient transfer of knowledge to the next generation".
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In Austria, the habilitation bestows the graduate with the *facultas docendi, venia legendi*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In many Central and Eastern Europe countries, the degree gives the *venia legendi*, Latin for "the permission to lecture", or *ius docendi*, "the right to teach", a specific academic subject at universities for a lifetime.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Higher doctorates may also be awarded as honorary degrees – either on an institution's own initiative or following a nomination – in recognition of public prestige, institutional service, philanthropy or professional achievement.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In a formal listing of qualifications, and often in other contexts, an honorary higher doctorate may be identified in various ways, including "DCL, *honoris causa*", "Hon LLD" or "LittD *h.c.*".
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Some Latin American countries award a postdoctoral degree, or *posdoctorado* involving structured postdoctoral studies and research.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Depending on the country, this may be called a *diploma de posdoctorado* (postdoctoral diploma), *título de Posdoctorado* (postdoctoral degree) or simply *posdoctorado* (postdoctorate).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Depending on the country, professional doctorates may also be research degrees at the same level as PhDs.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The relationship between research and practice is considered important and professional degrees with little or no research content are typically aimed at professional performance.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] The definition for a professional doctorate does not include a requirement for either a dissertation or study beyond master's level, in contrast to the definition for research doctorates ("doctor's degree – research/scholarship").
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] However, individual programs may have different requirements.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] There is also a category of "doctor's degree – other" for doctorates that do not fall into either the "professional practice" or "research/scholarship" categories.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] All of these are considered doctoral degrees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In contrast to the US, many countries reserve the term "doctorate" for research degrees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] If, as in Canada and Australia, professional degrees bear the name "Doctor of ...", etc., it is made clear that these are not doctorates.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Examples of this include Doctor of Medicine (MD), Doctor of Dental Surgery (DDS) and Juris Doctor (JD).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In the Philippines, the University of the Philippines Open University offers a Doctor of Communication (DComm) professional doctorate.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] All doctorates in the UK and Ireland are third cycle qualifications in the Bologna Process, comparable to US research doctorates.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Although all doctorates are research degrees, professional doctorates normally include taught components, while the name PhD/DPhil is normally used for doctorates purely by thesis.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Professional, practitioner, or practice-based doctorates such as the DClinPsy, DPsych, MD, DHSc, EdD, DBA, EngD and DAg are full academic doctorates.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] They are at the same level as the PhD in the national qualifications frameworks; they are not first professional degrees but are "often post-experience qualifications" in which practice is considered important in the research context.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] In 2009 there were 308 professional doctorate programs in the UK, up from 109 in 1998, with the most popular being the EdD (38 institutions), DBA (33), EngD/DEng (22), MD/DM (21), and DClinPsy/DClinPsych/ClinPsyD (17).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Similarly, in Australia, the term "professional doctorate" is sometimes applied to the *Scientiae Juridicae Doctor* (SJD), which, like the UK professional doctorates, is a research degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] When a university wishes to formally recognize an individual's contributions to a particular field or philanthropic efforts, it may choose to grant a doctoral degree *honoris causa* ('for the sake of the honor'), waiving the usual requirements for granting the degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p01] Some universities do not award honorary degrees; for example, Cornell University, the University of Virginia, and Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In Argentina the doctorate (*doctorado*) is the highest academic degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The intention is that candidates produce original contributions in their field knowledge within a frame of academic excellence.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] A dissertation or thesis is prepared under the supervision of a tutor or director.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] It is reviewed by a Doctoral Committee composed of examiners external to the program and at least one examiner external to the institution.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The degree is conferred after a successful dissertation defence.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In 2006, there were approximately 2,151 postgraduate careers in the country, of which 14% were doctoral degrees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Doctoral programs in Argentina are overseen by the National Commission for University Evaluation and Accreditation, an agency in Argentina's Ministry of Education, Science and Technology.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The Australian Qualifications Framework (AQF) categorizes tertiary qualifications into ten levels that are numbered from one to ten in ascending order of complexity and depth.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Of these qualification levels, six are for higher education qualifications and are numbered from five to ten.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Doctoral degrees occupy the highest of these levels: level ten.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] All doctoral degrees involve research and this is a defining characteristic of them.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] There are three categories of doctoral degrees recognized by the AQF: research doctorates, professional doctorates and higher doctorates.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Research doctorates and professional doctorates are both completed as part of a programme of study and supervised research.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Both have entry requirements of the student having a supervisor that has agreed to supervise their research, along with the student possessing an honours degree with upper second-class honours or better or a master's degree with a substantial research component.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Research doctorates are typically titled Doctor of Philosophy and they are awarded on the basis of an original and significant contribution to knowledge.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Professional doctorates are typically titled Doctor of (field of study) and they are awarded on the basis of an original and significant contribution to professional practice.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Typically, to be eligible to be awarded a higher doctorate a student must have completed a research doctorate at least seven to ten years prior to submitting the research portfolio used to award them a higher doctorate.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Doctoral candidates are normally required to have a master's degree in a related field.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Exceptions are based on their individual academic merit.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] A second and a third foreign language are other common requirements, although the requirements regarding proficiency commonly are not strict.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The admissions process varies by institution.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Some require candidates to take tests while others base admissions on a research proposal application and interview only.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In both instances however, a faculty member must agree prior to admission to supervise the applicant.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Requirements usually include satisfactory performance in advanced graduate courses, passing an oral qualifying exam and submitting a thesis that must represent an original and relevant contribution to existing knowledge.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The thesis is examined in a final public oral exam administered by at least five faculty members, two of whom must be external.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] After completion, which normally consumes 4 years, the candidate is commonly awarded the degree of *Doutor* (Doctor) followed by the main area of specialization, e.g.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] *Doutor em Direito* (Doctor of Laws), *Doutor em Ciências da Computação* (Doctor of Computer Sciences), *Doutor em Filosofia* (Doctor of Philosophy), *Doutor em Economia* (Doctor of Economics), *Doutor em Engenharia* (Doctor of Engineering) or *Doutor em Medicina* (Doctor of Medicine).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The generic title of *Doutor em Ciências* (Doctor of Sciences) is normally used to refer collectively to doctorates in the natural sciences (i.e.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] All graduate programs in Brazilian public universities are tuition-free (mandated by the Brazilian constitution).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Some graduate students are additionally supported by institutional scholarships granted by federal government agencies like CNPq (*Conselho Nacional de Desenvolvimento Científico e Tecnológico*) and CAPES (*Coordenação de Aperfeiçoamento do Pessoal de Ensino Superior*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Personal scholarships are provided by the various FAP's (*Fundações de Amparo à Pesquisa*) at the state level, especially FAPESP in the state of São Paulo, FAPERJ in the state of Rio de Janeiro and FAPEMIG in the state of Minas Gerais.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Competition for graduate financial aid is intense and most scholarships support at most 2 years of master's studies and 4 years of doctoral studies.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The normal monthly stipend for doctoral students in Brazil is between US$500 and $1000.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] A degree of *Doutor* usually enables an individual to apply for a junior faculty position equivalent to a US assistant professor.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Progression to full professorship, known as *Professor Titular*, requires that the candidate be successful in a competitive public exam and normally takes additional years.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In the federal university system, doctors who are admitted as junior faculty members may progress (usually by seniority) to the rank of associate professor, then become eligible to take the competitive exam for vacant full professorships.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In recent years some initiatives as jointly supervised doctorates (e.g.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] "cotutelles") have become increasingly common in the country, as part of the country's efforts to open its universities to international students.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] *dr.phil.*, *Doctor Philosophiae*, for humanistic and STEM subjects) – the higher doctorate – introduced in 1479.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The second part of the title communicates the field of study – e.g.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] *dr.scient* (in the sciences), *dr.jur* (in law), *dr.theol* (in theology).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] For the ph.d. degree, the candidates (ph.d. students or fellows) – who are required to have a master's degree – enroll at a ph.d. school at a university and participate in a research training program, at the end of which they each submit a thesis and defend it orally at a formal disputation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In the disputation, the candidates defend their theses against three official opponents, and may take opponents or questions from those present in the auditorium *(ex auditorio)*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The official opponents are required to be full professors.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The candidate is required to have a master's degree, but not necessarily a ph.d.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The original vision was purported to be to phase out the higher doctorate in favor of the ph.d.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] (or merge the two), but so far, there are no signs of this happening.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Many Danish academics with permanent positions wrote ph.d. dissertations in the 90s when the system was new, since at that time, a ph.d. degree or equivalent qualifications began to be required for certain academic positions in Denmark.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Until the late 20th century, the higher doctorate was a condition for attaining full professorship; it is no longer required *per se* for any positions, but is considered amply equivalent to the ph.d. when applying for academic positions.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In Egypt, the highest degree of doctorate is awarded by Al-Azhar University, which grants habilitation (Arabic: العالمية, romanized: *ālimiyya*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The medical doctorate (abbreviated as M.D.) is equivalent to the Ph.D. degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] To earn an M.D. in a science specialty, one must have a master's degree (M.Sc.) (or two diplomas before the introduction of the M.Sc. degree in Egypt) before applying.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The M.D. degree involves courses in the field and defending a dissertation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] It takes on average three to five years.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Many postgraduate medical and surgical specialties students earn a doctorate.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] After finishing a 6-year medical school and one-year internship (house officer), physicians and surgeons earn the M.B.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] B.Ch. degree, which is equivalent to a US MD degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] They can then apply to earn a master's degree or a speciality diploma, then an MD degree in a specialty.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The Egyptian M.D. degree is written using the name of one's specialty.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] (Geriatrics) means a doctorate in Geriatrics, which is equivalent to a Ph.D. in Geriatrics.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The Finnish requirement for the entrance into doctoral studies is a master's degree or equivalent.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] All universities have the right to award doctorates.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The *ammattikorkeakoulu* institutes (institutes of higher vocational education that are not universities but often called "Universities of Applied Sciences" in English) do not award doctoral or other academic degrees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Entrance to a doctoral program is available only for holders of a master's degree; there is no honors procedure for recruiting those with only a bachelor's degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Entrance is not as controlled as in undergraduate studies, where a strict numerus clausus is applied.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Usually, a prospective student discusses their plans with a professor.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] If the professor agrees to accept the student, the student applies for admission.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The professor may recruit students to their group.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Formal acceptance does not imply funding.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The student must obtain funding either by working in a research unit or through private scholarships.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Funding is more available for natural and engineering sciences than in letters.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Sometimes, normal work and research activity are combined.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Prior to introduction of the Bologna process, Finland required at least 42 credit weeks (1,800 hours) of formal coursework.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The requirement was removed in 2005, leaving the decision to individual universities, which may delegate the authority to faculties or individual professors.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In Engineering and Science, required coursework varies between 40 and 70 ECTS.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The duration of graduate studies varies.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] It is possible to graduate three years after the master's degree, while much longer periods are not uncommon.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The study ends with a dissertation, which must present substantial new scientific/scholarly knowledge.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The dissertation can either be a monograph or it an edited collection of 3 to 7 journal articles.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Students unable or unwilling to write a dissertation may qualify for a licentiate degree by completing the coursework requirement and writing a shorter thesis, usually summarizing one year of research.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] When the dissertation is ready, the faculty names two expert pre-examiners with doctoral degrees from the outside the university.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] During the pre-examination process, the student may receive comments on the work and respond with modifications.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] After the pre-examiners approve, the doctoral candidate applies the faculty for permission to print the thesis.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] When granting this permission, the faculty names the *opponent* for the thesis defence, who must also be an outside expert, with at least a doctorate.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In all Finnish universities, long tradition requires that the printed dissertation hang on a cord by a public university noticeboard for at least ten days prior to for the dissertation defence.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The doctoral dissertation takes place in public.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The opponent and the candidate conduct a formal debate, usually wearing white tie, under the supervision of the thesis supervisor.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Family, friends, colleagues and the members of the research community customarily attend the defence.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] After a formal entrance, the candidate begins with an approximately 20-minute popular lecture (*lectio praecursoria*), that is meant to introduce laymen to the thesis topic.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The opponent follows with a short talk on the topic, after which the pair critically discuss the dissertation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The proceedings take two to three hours.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] At the end the opponent presents their final statement and reveals whether he/she will recommend that the faculty accept it.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Any member of the public then has an opportunity to raise questions, although this is rare.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Immediately after the defence, the supervisor, the opponent and the candidate drink coffee with the public.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Usually, the attendees of the defence are given the printed dissertation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In the evening, the passed candidate hosts a dinner (Finnish: *karonkka*) in honour of the opponent.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Usually, the candidate invites their family, colleagues and collaborators.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Doctoral graduates are often Doctors of Philosophy (*filosofian tohtori*), but many fields retain their traditional titles: Doctor of Medicine (*lääketieteen tohtori*), Doctor of Science in technology (*tekniikan tohtori*), Doctor of Science in arts (Art and Design), etc.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The doctorate is a formal requirement for a docenture or professor's position, although these in practice require postdoctoral research and further experience.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Exceptions may be granted by the university governing board, but this is uncommon, and usually due to other work and expertise considered equivalent.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] There was also the less prestigious "university doctorate", ***doctorat d'université***, which could be received for the submission of a single thesis.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In the 1950s, the *Doctorat ès lettres* was renamed to *Doctorat d'État*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] After 1984, only one type of doctoral degree remained: the "doctorate" (*Doctorat*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] A special diploma was created called the "Habilitation to Supervise Research" (also translated as "accreditation to supervise research"; *Habilitation à diriger des recherches*), a professional qualification to supervise doctoral work.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Now habilitation is a prerequisite to the title of professor in university (*Professeur des universités*) and to the title of Research Director (*Directeur de recherche*) in national public research agency such as CNRS, INRIA, or INRAE.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Today, the doctorate (*doctorat*) is a research-only degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] It is a national degree and its requirements are fixed by the minister of higher education and research.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Only public institutions award the doctorate.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] It can be awarded in any field of study.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The writing of a comprehensive thesis constitutes the bulk of the doctoral work.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] While the length of the thesis varies according to the discipline, it is rarely less than 150 pages, and often substantially more.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Some 15,000 new doctoral matriculations occur every year and ≈10,000 doctorates are awarded.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Doctoral candidates can apply for a three-year fellowship.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The most well known is the *Contrat Doctoral* (4,000 granted every year with a gross salary of 2300 euros per month as of January 2026).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Since 2002, candidates follow in-service training, but there is no written examination for the doctorate.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The candidate has to write a thesis that is read by two external reviewers.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The head of the institution decides whether the candidate can defend the thesis, after considering the external reviews.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The jury members are designated by the head of the institution.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The candidate's supervisor and the external reviewers are generally jury members.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The maximum number of jury members is 8.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The defense generally lasts 45 minutes in scientific fields, followed by 1 – 2+1⁄2 hours of questions from the jury or other doctors present.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The jury then deliberates in private and then declares the candidate admitted or "postponed".
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] New regulations were set in 2016 and do not award distinctions.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The title of doctor (*docteur*) can also be used by medical and pharmaceutical practitioners who hold a doctor's State diploma (*diplôme d'État de docteur*, distinct from the *doctorat d'État* mentioned above).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] A guideline with good practices and legal analysis has been published in 2018 by the Association nationale des docteurs (ANDès) and the Confédération des Jeunes Chercheurs (CJC) with funding from the French Ministry of research.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Doctoral degrees in Germany are research doctorates and are awarded by a process called ***Promotion***.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Most doctorates are awarded with specific Latin designations for the field of research (except for engineering, where the designation is German), instead of a general name for all fields (such as the Ph.D.).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The concept of a US-style professional doctorate as an entry-level professional qualification does not exist.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Professional doctorates obtained in other countries, not requiring a thesis or not being third cycle qualifications under the Bologna process, can only be used postnominally, e.g., "Max Mustermann, MD", and do not allow the use of the title Dr.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In medicine, "doctoral" dissertations are often written alongside undergraduate study therefore, European Research Council decided in 2010 that such Dr. med. degrees do not meet the international standards of a Ph.D. research degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The duration of the doctorate depends on the field: a doctorate in medicine may take less than a full-time year to complete; those in other fields, two to six years.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Over fifty doctoral designations exist, many of them rare or no longer in use.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] As a title, the degree is commonly written in front of the name in abbreviated form, e.g., *Dr. rer. nat.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Max Mustermann*, dropping the designation entirely.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] However, leaving out the designation is only allowed when the doctorate degree is not an honorary doctorate, which must be indicated by *Dr. h.c.* (from Latin honoris causa).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Although the honorific does not become part of the name, holders can demand that the title appear in official documents.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The honorific is commonly used in formal letters.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] For holders of other titles, only the highest title is mentioned.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Schmidt", for a person who would be addressed as "Prof.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In the German university system it is common to write two doctoral theses, the **inaugural thesis** (*Inauguraldissertation*), completing a course of study, and the habilitation thesis (*Habilitationsschrift*), which opens the road to a professorship.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Upon completion of the habilitation thesis, a *Habilitation* is awarded, which is indicated by appending *habil.* (*habilitata/habilitatus*) to the doctorate, e.g., *Dr. rer. nat. habil.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] It is considered as an additional academic qualification rather than an academic degree formally.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] It qualifies the owner to teach at German universities (*facultas docendi*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The holder of a *Habilitation* receives the authorization to teach a certain subject (*venia legendi*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] This has been the traditional prerequisite for attaining *Privatdozent* (PD) and employment as a full university professor.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] With the introduction of *Juniorprofessuren*—around 2005—as an alternative track towards becoming a professor at universities (with tenure), *Habilitation* is no longer the only university career track.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In India, doctorates are offered by universities.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Entry requirements include a master's degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Some universities consider undergraduate degrees in professional areas such as engineering, medicine or law as qualifications for pursuing doctorate level degrees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Entrance examinations are held for almost all programs.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In most universities, the duration of coursework and writing the thesis is 3–7 years.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The most common doctoral degree is a Ph.D.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] In Ireland, doctoral qualifications are classified at Level 10 of the National Framework of Qualifications (NFQ).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The major award types at Level 10 are the doctoral degree and the higher doctorate.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The Irish NFQ is aligned with the Framework for Qualifications of the European Higher Education Area, which supports the international recognition of Irish research degrees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Ireland has a National Framework for Doctoral Education, which is intended to support excellence in all forms of doctoral education.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The revised 2023 framework sets out principles for doctoral education, including an original contribution to knowledge, a high-quality research environment, supervision and examination arrangements, and a final research thesis comprising work of publishable quality.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Professional doctorates in Ireland are also doctoral-level qualifications.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Quality and Qualifications Ireland states that validation of a professional doctorate requires research accreditation at NFQ Level 10 in the relevant discipline area.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Until the introduction of the *dottorato di ricerca* in the mid-1980s, the *laurea* generally constituted the highest academic degree obtainable in Italy.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The first institution in Italy to create a doctoral program was Scuola Normale Superiore di Pisa in 1927 under the historic name *"Diploma di Perfezionamento"*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The *dottorato di ricerca* was introduced by law and presidential decree in 1980, in a reform of academic teaching, training and experimentation in organisation and teaching methods.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Italy uses a three-level degree system following the Bologna Process.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The first-level degree, called a *laurea* (bachelor's degree), requires three years and a short thesis.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The second-level degree, called a *laurea magistrale* (master's degree), is obtained after two additional years, specializing in a branch of the field.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] This degree requires more advanced thesis work, usually involving academic research or an internship.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The final degree is called a *dottorato di ricerca* (Ph.D.) and is obtained after three years of academic research on the subject and a thesis.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Alternatively, after obtaining the *laurea* or the *laurea magistrale*, one can complete a "master's" (first-level master's after the *laurea* or second-level master's after the *laurea magistrale*) of one or two years, usually including an internship.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] An Italian "master's" is not the same as a master's degree; it is intended to be more focused on professional training and practical experience.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Regardless of the field of study, the title for Bachelors Graduate students is *Dottore/Dottoressa* (abbrev.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] *Dott.*/*Dott.ssa*, or as *Dr.*), not to be confused with the title for the Ph.D., which is instead *Dottore/Dottoressa di Ricerca*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] A *laurea magistrale* grants instead the title of *Dottore/Dottoressa magistrale*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Graduates in the fields of Education, Art and Music are also called *Dr.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Prof.* (or simply *Professore*) or *Maestro*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Many professional titles, such as *ingegnere* (engineer) are awarded only upon passing a post-graduation examination (*esame di stato*), and registration in the relevant professional association.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Until the 1990s, most natural science and engineering doctorates in Japan were earned by industrial researchers in Japanese companies.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] These degrees were awarded by the employees' former university, usually after years of research in industrial laboratories.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The only requirement is submission of a dissertation, along with articles published in well-known journals.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] This program is called *ronbun hakushi (hakase)* (論文博士).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] It produced the majority of engineering doctoral degrees from national universities.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] University-based doctoral programs called *katei hakushi (hakase)* (課程博士), are gradually replacing these degrees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] By 1994, more doctoral engineering degrees were earned for research within university laboratories (53%) than industrial research laboratories (47%).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] Since 1978, Japan Society for the Promotion of Science (JSPS) has provided tutorial and financial support for promising researchers in Asia and Africa.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] The only professional doctorate in Japan is the Juris Doctor, known as *hōmu hakushi* (法務博士) The program generally lasts two or three years.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] This curriculum is professionally oriented, but unlike in the US the program does not provide education sufficient for a law license.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p02] All candidates for a bar license must pass the bar exam (*shihou shiken*), attend the Legal Training and Research Institute and pass the practical exam (*nikai shiken* or *shihou shushusei koushi*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] After successful completion of the first year of university, the student was awarded the propaedeutic diploma (not a degree).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In some fields, this diploma was abolished in the 1980s.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In physics and mathematics, the student could directly obtain a *kandidaats* (candidate) diploma in two years.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The candidate diploma was all but abolished by 1989.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] It used to be attained after completion of the majority of courses of the academic study (usually after completion of course requirements of the third year in the program), after which the student was allowed to begin work on their doctorandus thesis.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The successful completion of this thesis conveyed the *doctoranda/us* title, implying that the student's initial studies were finished.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In addition to these 'general' degrees, specific titles equivalent to the *doctorandus* degree were awarded for law: *meester* (master) (mr.), and for engineering: *ingenieur* (engineer) (ir.).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Following the Bologna protocol the Dutch adopted the Anglo-Saxon system of academic degrees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The old candidate's degree was revived to become the bachelor's degree and the *doctorandus* (mr and ir degrees) was replaced by master's degrees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Students can only enroll in a doctorate system after completing a research university level master's degree; although dispensation can be granted on a case-by-case basis after scrutiny of the individual's portfolio.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Research can also be conducted without official research assistant status, for example through a business-sponsored research laboratory.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The doctor's title is the highest academic title in the Netherlands and Flanders.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In research doctorates the degree is always Ph.D. or dr. with no distinction between disciplines, and can only be granted by research universities.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Every Ph.D. thesis has to be promoted by a research university staff member holding ius promovendi (the right to promote).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In the Netherlands all full professors have ius promovendi, as well as other academic staff granted this right on individual basis by the board of their university (almost always senior associate professors).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The promotor has the role of principal advisor and determines whether the thesis quality suffices and can be submitted to the examining committee.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The examining committee is appointed by the academic board of the university based on recommendation of the promotor and consists of experts in the field.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The examining committee reviews the thesis manuscript and has to approve or fail the thesis.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Failures at this stage are rare because promotors generally do not allow work to be submutted they deem inadequate to the examining committee, supervisors and promotor lose prestige among their peers should they allow a substandard thesis to be submitted.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] After examining committee approval, the candidate publishes the thesis (generally with DOI: and ISBN indices) and sends it to the examining committee, colleagues, friends and family with an invitation to the public defence.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Additional copies are kept in the university library and the Royal Library of the Netherlands.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The degree is awarded in a formal, public, defence session, in which the thesis is defended against critical questions of the "opposition" (the examining committee).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Specific formalities differ between universities, for example whether a public presentation is given, either before or during the session, specific phrasing in the procedure, and dress code.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In most protocols, candidates can be supported by paranymphs, a largely ceremonial role, although they are formally allowed to take over the defence on behalf of the candidate.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Doctoral candidates The actual defence lasts exactly the assigned time slot (45 minutes to 1 hour exactly depending on the university) after which the defence is suspended by the bedel who stops the examination with the Latin phrase "Hora Est" (it is time).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Examinations are thus stopped on the clock, frequently mid sentence.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Failure during this session is possible, but extremely rare.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Dutch doctors may use PhD behind their name or the uncapitalized dr. before their name.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Those who obtained a degree in a foreign country can only use the Dutch title dr. if their grade is approved as equivalent by the *Dienst Uitvoering Onderwijs* though according to the opportunity principle, little effort is spent in identifying such fraud.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Those who have multiple doctor (dr.) titles may use the title dr.mult.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Those who have received honoris causa doctorates may use dr.h.c. before their own name.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In 2023, a pilot started at universities of applied sciences with a professional doctoral programme, in which the focus is on applying knowledge to improve or solve professional processes or products.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In Belgium's Flemish Community the doctorandus title was only used by those who actually started their doctoral work.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Doctorandus is still used as a synonym for a Ph.D. student.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The *licentiaat* (licensee) title was in use for a regular graduate until the Bologna reform changed the licentiaat degree to the master's degree (the Bologna reform abolished the two-year kandidaat degree and introduced a three-year academic bachelor's degree instead).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In Poland, an academic degree of *doktor* 'doctor' is awarded in sciences and arts upon an examination and defence of a doctoral dissertation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] As Poland is a signatory to the Bologna Process, doctoral studies are a third cycle of studies following the bachelor's (*licencjat*) and master's (*magister*) degrees or their equivalents.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Doctoral student is known as *doktorant* (masculine form) or *doktorantka* (feminine form).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Doctorate is awarded within specified branch and discipline of science or art by university or research institute accredited by the minister responsible for higher education.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The title is abbreviated to *dr* in nominative case.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Doctors may further undergo the habilitation process.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Introduced in 1819 in the Russian Empire, the academic title *Doctor of the Sciences* (Russian: Доктор наук) marks the highest academic level achievable by a formal process.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The title was abolished with the end of the Empire in 1917 and revived by the USSR in 1934 along with a new (lower) complementary degree of a *Candidate [Doctor] of the Sciences'* (Russian: Кандидат наук).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] This system has been used since with minor adjustments.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The *Candidate of the Sciences* title is usually seen as roughly equivalent to research doctorates in Western countries while the *Doctor of the Sciences* title is relatively rare and retains its exclusivity.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Most "Candidates" never reach the "Doctor of the Sciences" title.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Similar title systems were adopted by many of the Soviet bloc countries.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Doctoral degrees are regulated by Royal Decree (R.D.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] They are granted by the university on behalf of the king.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Its diploma has the force of a public document.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The Ministry of Science keeps a national registry of theses called TESEO.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] According to the National Institute of Statistics (INE), fewer than 5% of M.Sc. degree holders are admitted to Ph.D. programmes.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] All doctoral programs are research-oriented.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Since September 2012 and regulated by Royal Decree (R.D.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] 99/2011) (in Spanish), three marks can be granted: Unsatisfactory (*No apto*), Pass (*Apto*) and "Cum laude" (*Apto Cum Laude*) as maximum mark.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In the public defense the doctor is notified if the thesis has passed or not passed.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The *Apto Cum Laude* mark is awarded after the public defense as the result of a private, anonymous vote.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] A unanimous vote of the reviewers nominates Doctors granted *Apto Cum Laude* for an "Extraordinary Award" (*Premio Extraordinario de Doctorado*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] An approved project earns a master's degree that grants access to a Ph.D. program and initiates the period of research.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] A doctorate is required in order to teach at a university.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Some universities offer an online Ph.D. model.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Only Ph.D. holders, Grandees and Dukes can sit and cover their heads in the presence of the King.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] From 1857, Complutense University was the only one in Spain authorised to confer the doctorate.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] This law remained in effect until 1954, when the University of Salamanca joined in commemoration of its septcentenary.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In 1970, the right was extended to all Spanish universities.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] All doctorate holders are reciprocally recognised as equivalent in Germany and Spain (according to the "Bonn Agreement of November 14, 1994").
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The doctorate has long existed in the UK as, originally, the second degree in divinity, law, medicine and music.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] But it was not until the late 19th century that the research doctorate, now known as the higher doctorate, was introduced.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The first higher doctorate was the Doctor of Science at Durham University, introduced in 1882.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The PhD was adopted in the UK following a joint decision in 1917 by British universities, although it took much longer for it to become established.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Oxford became the first university to institute the new degree, although naming it the DPhil.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The PhD was often distinguished from the earlier higher doctorates by distinctive academic dress.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] At Cambridge, for example, PhDs wear a master's gown with scarlet facings rather than the full scarlet gown of the higher doctors, while the University of Wales gave PhDs crimson gowns rather than scarlet.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Professional doctorates were introduced in Britain in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The earliest professional doctorates were in the social sciences, including the Doctor of Business Administration (DBA), Doctor of Education (EdD) and Doctor of Clinical Psychology (DClinPsy).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] *Professional / practice-based / practitioner doctorates* – e.g.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In the UK, the doctorate is a qualification awarded at FHEQ level 8/level 12 of the FQHEIS on the national qualifications frameworks.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The higher doctorates are stated to be "A higher level of award", which is not covered by the qualifications frameworks.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] These are the most common doctorates in the UK and are normally awarded as PhDs.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] While the master/apprentice model was traditionally used for British PhDs, since 2003 courses have become more structured, with students taking courses in research skills and receiving training for professional and personal development.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] However, the assessment of the PhD remains based on the production of a thesis or equivalent and its defence at a *viva voce* oral examination, normally held in front of at least two examiners, one internal and one external.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Access to PhDs normally requires an upper second class or first class bachelor's degree, or a master's degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Courses normally last three years, although it is common for students to be initially registered for MPhil degrees and then formally transferred onto the PhD after a year or two.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Students who are not considered likely to complete a PhD may be offered the opportunity to complete an MPhil instead.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Integrated doctorates, originally known as 'New Route PhDs', were introduced from 2000 onwards.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] These integrate teaching at master's level during the first one or two years of the degree, either alongside research or as a preliminary to starting research.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] These courses usually offer a master's-level exit degree after the taught courses are completed.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] While passing the taught elements is often required, examination of the final doctorate is still by thesis (or equivalent) alone.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The duration of integrated doctorates is a minimum of four years, with three years spent on the research component.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In 2013, Research Councils UK issued a 'Statement of Expectations for Postgraduate Training', which lays out the expectations for training in PhDs funded by the research councils.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The statement also encourages peer-group development through cohort training and/or Graduate schools.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Higher doctorates are awarded in recognition of a substantial body of original research undertaken over the course of many years.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Usually an examination fee is required, with the examiners examining the whole body of work submitted rather than a single thesis.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] For Doctors of Music, the traditional form of submission is a large body of musical compositions within a portfolio plus commentary, though some universities may allow for other forms of work to be submitted rather than purely musical compositions.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The higher doctorate is similar in some respects to the habilitation in some European countries.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] However, the purpose of the award is significantly different.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] While the habilitation formally determines whether an academic is suitably qualified to be a university professor, the higher doctorate does not qualify the holder for a position but rather recognises their contribution to research.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The DSc was offered by all 49 responding institutions in 2008 and 15 out of 16 in 2013 and the DLitt by only one less in each case, while the DD was offered in 10 responding institutions in 2008 and 3 in 2013.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In terms of number of higher doctorates awarded (not including honorary doctorates) the DSc was most popular, but the number of awards was very low: the responding institutions had averaged an award of at most one earned higher doctorate per year over the period 2003–2013.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Award of substantive higher doctorates remain relatively rare, due to many people not being aware of them or due to the fact that people think they are only given out as honorary degrees on graduation day.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] This has led to many institutions no longer offering/awarding them as substantive degrees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Those that do still offer them often do not openly advertise or promote them due to the costs of having to examine for them as well as the lack of interest in them from academic staff members who might view holding a professorship the pinnacle of their careers rather than holding a higher doctorate.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Most British universities award degrees *honoris causa* to recognise individuals who have made a substantial contribution to a particular field.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Usually an appropriate higher doctorate is used in these circumstances, depending on the candidate's achievements.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] However, some universities differentiate between honorary and substantive doctorates, using the degree of Doctor of the University (D.Univ.) for these purposes, and reserve the higher doctorates for formal academic research.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] These degrees are substantive, not honorary, degrees awarded by the Archbishop of Canterbury in their own right under previous Papal authority and existing UK legislation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] U.S. research doctorates are awarded for advanced study followed by successfully completing and defending independent research presented in the form of a dissertation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Professional degrees may use the term "doctor" in their titles, such as Juris Doctor and Doctor of Medicine, but these degrees rarely contain an independent research component and are not research doctorates.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Law school graduates, although awarded the J.D. degree, are not normally addressed as "doctor".
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In legal studies, the Doctor of Juridical Science is considered the equivalent to a Ph.D.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Many American universities offer the PhD followed by a professional doctorate or joint PhD with a professional degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Often, PhD work is sequential to the professional degree, e.g., a PhD in law after a JD or equivalent, in physical therapy after a DPT, and in pharmacy after a Pharm.D.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Such professional degrees are referred to as an entry-level doctorate program, while the Ph.D. is a post-professional doctorate.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The most common research doctorate in the United States is the Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] This degree was first awarded in the U.S. at the 1861 Yale University commencement.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The University of Pennsylvania followed in 1871, with Cornell University (1872), Harvard (1873), Michigan (1876) and Princeton (1879) following suit.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Controversy and opposition followed the introduction of the Ph.D. into the U.S. educational system, lasting into the 1950s, as it was seen as an unnecessary artificial transplant from the German educational system, which corrupted a system based on England's Oxbridge model.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Ph.D.s and other research doctorates in the U.S. typically entail successful completion of coursework, passing a comprehensive examination, and defending a dissertation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The median number of years for completion of U.S. doctoral degrees is seven.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Doctoral applicants were previously required to have a master's degree, but many programs accept students immediately following undergraduate studies.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Many programs gauge the potential of applicants to their program and grant a master's degree upon completion of the necessary course work.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] When so admitted, the student is expected to have mastered the material covered in the master's degree despite not holding one, though this tradition is under heavy criticism.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Successfully finishing Ph.D. qualifying exams confers Ph.D. candidate status, allowing dissertation work to begin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] The International Affairs Office of the U.S.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Department of Education has listed 18 frequently awarded research doctorate titles identified by the National Science Foundation (NSF) as representing degrees equivalent in research content to the Ph.D.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Many fields offer professional doctorates (or professional master's degrees) for fields such as engineering, pharmacy, and medicine that require such degrees for professional practice or licensure.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Some of these degrees are also termed "first professional degrees", since they are the first field-specific master's or doctoral degrees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] A Doctor of Engineering (DEng) is a professional oriented research degree considered equivalent to a PhD.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] However a PhD in Engineering includes original theory-based research while DEng degrees focus on applied research solutions.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] DEng students defend their dissertation or praxis at the end of their study before a committee in order to be conferred a degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] A Doctor of Pharmacy is awarded as the professional degree in pharmacy replacing a bachelor's degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] It is the only professional pharmacy degree awarded in the US.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Pharmacy programs vary in length between four years for matriculants with a B.S./B.A. to six years for others.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In the twenty-first century professional doctorates appeared in other fields, such as the Doctor of Audiology in 2007.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Advanced Practice Registered Nurses were expected to completely transition to the Doctor of Nursing Practice by 2015, and physical therapists to the Doctor of Physical Therapy by 2020.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Professional associations play a central role in this transformation amid criticisms on the lack of proper criteria to assure appropriate rigor.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In many cases master's-level programs were relabeled as doctoral programs.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In the US doctoral degrees can be revoked or rescinded by the university that awarded them.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] Possible reasons include plagiarism, criminal or unethical activities of the holder, or malfunction or manipulation of academic evaluation processes.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] In the Netherlands it had long been unclear whether a university can revoke a doctoral degree as this is not explicitly mentioned in the education laws.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/doctorate-p03] However, in an appeal to the revocation of a degree in 2017, the high court of the Netherlands ruled in 2024, that if the candidate has consciously committed fraud the granting university can indeed revoke a degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] The **Endangered Languages Archive** (**ELAR**) is a digital archive for materials on endangered languages, based at Berlin-Brandenburg Academy of Sciences and Humanities (BBAW).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] The Archive preserves digital collections, including audio and video recordings, of endangered languages around the world.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] ELAR is part of the worldwide community of language archives (DELAMAN and the Open Language Archives Community).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] ELAR's main aim is to preserve and publish collections of audio and video recordings, transcriptions and translations, dictionaries, and primers in and of endangered languages created with and by speakers of the endangered languages.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] The archive also digitises legacy collections in analogue formats saving them from deterioration and making them accessible to the speaker and their descendants, scholars, and the public.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] The collection currently contains over 550 deposits recorded in over 70 different countries, the majority of which are the results of Endangered Languages Documentation Project (ELDP) documentation projects funded by the Arcadia Fund.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] The catalogue of archived materials can be freely searched via the Open Languages Archives Community.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] The endangered languages collections at ELAR can be accessed free of charge.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] ELAR also provides training in all aspects of the creation of digital collections to archiving collections.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] These entail metadata creation, data management, formats, curation as well as digitisation of analogue formats.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] The archive was originally funded in 2002 as part of a donation by the Arcadia Fund to support the documentation of endangered languages, to train students and scholars in language documentation and to digitally preserve and publish the collections.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] ELAR was housed in and supported by the SOAS University of London library from 2015 until their move to the BBAW in 2021.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] David Nathan was director during the first decade of the archive's existence until 2014, when the role was taken over by Mandana Seyfeddinipur, who is also head of ELDP.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] From July, 2021, ELAR has been housed at the Berlin-Brandenburg Academy of Sciences and Humanities (German: *Berlin-Brandenburgische Akademie der Wissenschaften*) in Berlin, Germany.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/endangered-languages-archive] ELAR is one of three partners of the CLARIN Knowledge Centre for Linguistic Diversity and Language Documentation (CKLD), providing its expertise to researchers and community members across Europe.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The **Free University of Berlin** (German: *Freie Universität Berlin*, often abbreviated as **FU Berlin** or simply **FU**) is a public research university in Berlin, Germany.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] It was founded in West Berlin in 1948 during the early Cold War period.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The Free University's name referred to West Berlin's status as part of the intellectual continuum of the Western "Free World" in contrast to Soviet-controlled East Berlin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Its main campus is located in Berlin-Dahlem in the Steglitz-Zehlendorf district.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] One of the foremost universities in Germany, it is internationally renowned for research in the humanities, social sciences, and natural and life sciences.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The Free University is one of thirteen leading German universities currently designated a "University of Excellence" according to the German Universities Excellence Initiative (*Exzellenzinitiative*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] It was the first Berlin university to be awarded this distinction and one of only six universities nationwide to be so recognised in all three consecutive rounds of the Excellence Initiative in 2006/2007, 2012 and 2019, most recently as a member of the Berlin University Alliance.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In university rankings, the FU Berlin is consistently ranked among the top 100 universities globally and in the top five nationally.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In 2026, 16 subjects at the FU Berlin were ranked among the top 100 in a global ranking.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] According to the Alexander von Humboldt Foundation, the university is the most frequently chosen study location in Germany for top international scientists and young academics.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Former and current staff include five Nobel laureates.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The FU Berlin has produced a total of 18 winners of the Leibniz Prize up to the year 2020.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The Free University of Berlin was established in West Berlin by faculty members and students on 4 December 1948.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] With American support, it was founded as the de facto Western continuation of the University of Berlin (before 1945 named the Friedrich Wilhelm University), which had reopened in 1946 in the Soviet sector of Berlin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In 1949, the University of Berlin, on its original site in East Berlin, was renamed the Humboldt University.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In January 1946, the formerly named Friedrich Wilhelm University, located in the Soviet sector of Berlin, was granted permission by the Soviet Military Administration in Germany (SMAD) to reopen as the University of Berlin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The university came under increased communist influence and repression, as it became a battlefield for the political disputes of the postwar period.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] This led to protests by students critical of the prevailing system.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Between 1945 and 1948, more than 18 students were brutally beaten and arrested or persecuted, and some were even executed by the Soviet secret police (NKVD).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] At the end of 1947, students demanded a university free from political influence.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The climax of the protests was reached on 23 April 1948: after three students were expelled from the university without a trial, about 2,000 students protested at the *Hotel Esplanade*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] By the end of April, the governor of the United States Army, Lucius D.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Clay, issued the order to legally examine the formation of a new university in the western sectors of Berlin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] On 19 June 1948, the "preparatory committee for establishing a free university" consisting of politicians, professors, administrative staff members, and students, met.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] With a manifesto titled "Request for establishing a free university in Berlin", the committee appealed to the public for support.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The municipal authorities of Berlin granted the foundation of a free university and requested the opening for the coming 1948/49 winter semester.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Meanwhile, the students' committee in the German Democratic Republic protested against the formation; the GDR described the new university as the "so-called free university" in official documents until the fall of the Berlin Wall.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The council-manager government accepted the by-law on 4 November 1948.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] This form was unique in Germany at that time, as the students had much more influence on the system than before.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Until the 1970s, the involvement of the students in the committees was slowly cut back while adapting to the model of the Western German universities in order to be fully recognized as an equivalent university.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] On 15 November 1948, the first lectures were held in the buildings of the Kaiser Wilhelm Society for the Advancement of Science.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The actual foundation took place on 4 December 1948 in the Titania Palace, the film theater with the biggest hall available in the western sectors of Berlin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Attendee at the event were not only scientists, politicians (the Governing Mayor Ernst Reuter amongst others) and students, but also representatives of American universities, among them Stanford University and Yale University.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The first elected president of the Free University of Berlin was the historian Friedrich Meinecke.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] By 1949, the Free University had registered 4,946 students.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Until the construction of the Berlin Wall in 1961, many students came from the Soviet sector, often supported through the *Währungsstipendium* of the senate.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] On 26 June 1963, the same day he delivered his *Ich bin ein Berliner* speech at Rathaus Schöneberg, John F.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Kennedy was awarded honorary citizen status by the Free University and gave a ceremonial speech in front of the Henry Ford building, in which he addressed the future of Berlin and Germany under the consideration of the motto of the FU.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Amongst the attendant crowd are also the Governing Mayor of West Berlin, Willy Brandt, and the Chancellor of West Germany, Konrad Adenauer.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Kennedy, visited the university in 1962 for the first time and in June 1964 to receive his honorary degree from the *Department of Philosophy*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The speech he held at the event was dedicated to John F.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Kennedy, who was assassinated the year before.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In the late 1960s, the Free University of Berlin was one of the main scenes of the West German student movement of '68, as a reaction to the global student protests during that time.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Significant issues included better living standards and education at the university, the Vietnam War, the presence of former Nazi Party members in the government as epitomized by the Globke affair, and continuing institutional authoritarianism.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] After the assassination of student Benno Ohnesorg and the attempt on the life of Rudi Dutschke, protests quickly escalated to violence throughout West Germany.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The events of the 68-movement provided the impulse for more openness, equality, and democracy in West German society.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] During the 1970s and the 1980s, the university became a *Massenuniversität* (*mass/mega university*) with 50,298 registered students in 1983.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] After reunification, the Free University of Berlin was the second-largest university in Germany (after LMU Munich) with 62,072 students in the winter term of 1991/92.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Shortly thereafter, the senate of Berlin decided to drastically reduce enrollment until 2003, the number of students shrank to 43,885 in the winter term of 2002/03.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Since 2000, the Free University of Berlin has revamped itself.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The university's research performance increased markedly with regard to the number of graduates, PhDs granted, and publications.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Since 2003, the FU Berlin has been regrouping its research capacities into interdisciplinary research focus areas called clusters.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Due to financial cutbacks and restructuring of medical schools in the same year, the medical institutions of the Free and Humboldt Universities of Berlin merged to create a joint department, the Charité – Universitätsmedizin Berlin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The year 2007 was another crucial year for the Free University of Berlin as it was the university with the most approved funding applications in the German Universities Excellence Initiative, and it is now one of nine elite German universities to receive funding for its future development strategy.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In the same year, the Free University of Berlin dedicated a monument to the founding students who were murdered during the protests.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The university presents its Freedom Award to personalities who have made a special contribution toward the cause of freedom.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The university received a total of 108 million euros from the Excellence Initiative for its approved projects between 2007 and 2012.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Based on its founding tradition, the Free University of Berlin seal to this day bears the Latin terms for Truth, Justice, and Liberty.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The designer of the seal was art historian and former president of the Free University of Berlin, Edwin Redslob.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Most of the facilities of the Free University of Berlin are located in the residential garden district of Dahlem in southwestern Berlin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Around the beginning of the 20th century, Dahlem was established as a center for research of the highest caliber.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The first new buildings housed government science agencies and new research institutes of the University of Berlin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The Kaiser Wilhelm Society – forerunner of the present-day Max Planck Society – was founded in 1911 and established several institutes in Dahlem.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] A dynamic group of researchers carried out pioneering research resulting in numerous Nobel Prizes.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Since its foundation, the Free University of Berlin has been using buildings formerly belonging to the Kaiser Wilhelm Society and, in addition, has added numerous architecturally innovative buildings.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The Free University of Berlin's central campus consists of building ensembles within walking distance of each other (about a 1.5 km radius).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The planners oriented themselves along the type of campus found in the United States – a novelty in post-war Germany.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The first independent structure to be completed on campus was the Henry Ford building, funded by the Ford Foundation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] To that point, the university was housed in several older structures around the neighborhood, including the Otto Hahn building, which houses the *Department of Biochemistry* to this day.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Thanks to further donations from the United States, the Free University of Berlin was able to construct several new central building complexes, including the Benjamin Franklin university clinic complex.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The largest single complex of university buildings is the *Rost- und Silberlaube*, which translates roughly to the "Rust and Silver Lodges".
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] This complex consists of a series of interlinked structures corresponding to either a deep bronze (hence, "rust") or shiny white ("silver") hue, surrounding a variety of leafy courtyards.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] It was complemented in 2005 by a new centerpiece, the brain-shaped Philological Library, designed by British architect Lord Norman Foster.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] With 43 ha and around 22,000 species of plants, FU's Berlin Botanical Garden in nearby Lichterfelde West is one of the largest of its kind.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The main campus in Dahlem is well connected to central Berlin by public transportation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The stations Dahlem Dorf and Freie Universität (Thielplatz) connect the university to the Berlin U-Bahn system's U3 line.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The Lichterfelde West station of the S1 line of the Berlin S-Bahn connects the university to Berlin Mitte.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The campus in Lankwitz, formerly part of a teacher training college, is now home to the department of earth sciences and a part of the university archives.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Until their move to Dahlem in 2008, the *Institute for Media and Communication Studies* was located there.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Most of the divisions of the *Department of Veterinary Medicine* are based in Düppel.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] It is 2 km southwest of the main campus and consists of numerous clinics and institutes, amongst them a small animal clinic, a clinic for horses and an institute of poultry diseases.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Since the formation of the FU in 1948, it has used public hospitals as part of the medical faculty.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Between 1959 and 1969, the "Steglitz Clinic", located in Lichterfelde West, about 3 km southeast of Dahlem, was built with large financial support from the United States.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The medical center became one of the biggest European medical establishments, unifying all institutes, clinics, and lecture halls.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In honor of the support by the United States, the clinic was renamed "University Clinic Benjamin Franklin".
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In 1994, it consisted of 36 scientific institutes and 1,200 hospital beds.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] After the merger in 2003, it became part of the Charité medical school.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The Berlin Geography Society, founded in 1828, the *Berlin University for Professional Studies,* and the German Archeological Institute (DAI) are also located on the campus.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In addition, Dahlem is an important location for the Berlin State Museums group, housing the Ethnological Museum of Berlin and the Museum of Asian Art.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] During the 1960s, a student village with 27 buildings was constructed near Schlachtensee (lake), serving as housing opportunities for students.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The Freie Universität Berlin University Library is one of the major academic libraries in Germany.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] It comprises the central library, several subject libraries, and the university archive.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Its holdings cover all academic disciplines represented at the university and include print and electronic resources, databases, journals, and digital research services.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The term "University Library" refers to all libraries of Freie Universität Berlin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] 39 is the central library, it was formerly known as the University Library.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Library holdings in many subject areas have been consolidated into larger subject libraries, reducing the total number of locations.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Notable library buildings include the Philological Library designed by Lord Norman Foster (opened 2005), and the Campus Library (opened 2015).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Holdings are researchable via the Primo Discovery System , which provides access to digital and print materials and external scholarly resources.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Digitisation projects continue to integrate additional collections.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The library operates digital research infrastructures, including the institutional repository Refubium for scholarly publications and research data, as well as services for open access, research data management, and digital publishing.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] It also maintains digital oral history collections and participates in the development of the cross-institutional portal Oral-History.Digital for integrated access to recorded interviews.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The executive board consists of the president (Prof.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Ziegler), an executive vice president (Prof.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Klaus Hoffmann-Holland), and three other vice presidents, as well as the Director of Administration and Finance (Dr.-Ing.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] There are also supporting offices for Public Affairs and the General Counsel for legal affairs.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The **ISQ** ("Institut für Schulqualität der Länder Berlin und Brandenburg", *Institute for Quality of Schools in Berlin and Brandenburg*) is an independent facility on the campus.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] It consults local schools and the senate to achieve and develop a high standard of school quality in Berlin and Brandenburg and closely cooperates with the *Department of Education and Psychology* of the FU.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The **Collegium Musicum** of Free University of Berlin was founded during the first semester in 1948/49.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Under conductor Karl Forster, it merged with the ensemble of Technische Universität Berlin in 1954.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Today, the Collegium Musicum has around 500 members from all fields of studies who spend their leisure time making music.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] It currently consists of five ensembles: a big choir, a chamber choir, two symphony orchestras, and a big band.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] There are frequently events on which the Collegium Musicum plays, for instance on ceremonies.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] With 12 academic departments (*Fachbereiche*) and three interdisciplinary central institutes, the university can be seen as an *universitas litterarum* (a traditional university where studies in all basic sciences is possible).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Despite the variety of subjects, apart from computer science, studies in the field of engineering can only be done at Technische Universität Berlin or universities of applied science (*Fachhochschulen*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] With 33,000 applicants for the undergraduate programs (Bachelor) in 2013, admissions at Free University of Berlin remain highly competitive as the university only offers about 4,300 places each year.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Due to the high numbers of applicants, most undergraduate programs at Free University of Berlin have limitations determined through the NC.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In some cases (especially Medicine, Psychology and Political Science), the NC every year is as high as 1.0 (*see Grades in Germany and Abitur*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Critical applicants which just scored slightly below the NC can be invited to a selective interview or an entry exam, depending on the department/faculty.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Applicants at Charité medical school who do not directly fulfill the NC-criteria have to pass an entry exam, which covers the basic fields of Mathematics, Biology, Chemistry, and Physics in addition to passing a selective interview.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Both results are then added to the Abitur grade.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The final decision depends on the results of the competitors.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Free University of Berlin operates on a semester calendar where the winter term begins on 1 October and ends on 31 March.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The exact same model can be found at almost every university in Germany.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The time when lectures are being held varies each year, normally beginning around mid-October and ending as early as mid-February.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Free University of Berlin offers a broad spectrum of subjects in over 190 degree programs.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] A speciality of the FU is the possibility to study a vast number of "small subjects" (e.g. theater and film studies, Egyptology, Byzantine studies, Jewish studies, Turkology, Sinology, Communication studies, Meteorology, Bioinformatics, Biochemistry) with a high level of specialization.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Due to the Bologna process, most of the undergraduate programs are now leading to the three-year Bachelor's degree with 180 ECTS.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] At the Free University of Berlin, Bachelor programs are generally divided into three categories: a regular Bachelor called "Mono-Bachelor", a combined Bachelor ("Kombi-Bachelor") consisting of two fields of study, and a combined Bachelor with a teaching option.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Besides the core subject(s), all students are required to complete a series of courses related to general professional skills (ABV).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The old Diplom and Magister artium programs are still running, but do not accept new admissions anymore.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In the fields of Medicine, Veterinary Medicine, Dentistry, Pharmacy, and Law, students enroll in programs with *Staatsexamen*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Free University of Berlin also offers a variety of graduate degrees, from the master's degree to doctoral degrees.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Apart from the regular Master's programs, there are a variety of international programs taught in English, especially in the life sciences.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Free University of Berlin does not charge any tuition fees in the classical sense.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Since 2003, public universities in Berlin introduced the model of semester contributions (*Semesterbeiträge*).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] It consists of an enrollment/re-registration fee, a contribution to the student union (*Studentenwerk*), a contribution for the student government and the fee for the semester ticket (public transportation pass) for the current semester.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The fees for the semester ticket is defined by a contract with the local transportation company, the Verkehrsverbund Berlin-Brandenburg and allows students to move freely in the ABC zones of Berlin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In the winter semester of 2013/14, students are required to pay €285.83 in total.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Since 2011, the Free University of Berlin has participated in the national "Germany Scholarship" program organized by the federal government, universities, and numerous private companies.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Talented and committed students can get €300 monthly.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In terms of external endowments by the DFG, Free University of Berlin ranks third behind the RWTH Aachen University and LMU Munich.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Between 2009 and 2013, 289 foreign guest researchers came to the university through fellowships granted by the renowned Alexander von Humboldt Foundation, making the FU the most popular destination for foreign researchers in Germany.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In the field of Earth sciences, the FU has contributed to various aeronautical missions, e.g. the Mars Express and the Cassini-Huygens to Saturn.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Excluding the Charité medical school, which is co-administered by the university with the Humboldt University, Free University of Berlin is currently the lead university for eight collaborative research centers of the German Research Foundation and also has five DFG research units.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] It is part of the Berlin University Alliance.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] As part of the *MATHEON – Mathematics for Key Technologies* research center of the DFG, Free University of Berlin together with the TU Berlin, HU Berlin and the Zuse Institute Berlin is working on mathematical modeling, simulation and optimization of real-world processes.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Twice every year, the "Dahlem Conferences" are held at the Free University of Berlin.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Over the course of one week, internationally renowned scientists and Nobel laureates come together and discuss current problems in all fields of study.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The annual "Einstein Lectures Dahlem" hosted by the university and several external institutions since 2005 are dedicated to Albert Einstein, who was the director of the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute of Physics for more than 15 years.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] It is an colloquium which presents fields in science which were influenced by Einstein's thinking.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The 2024 British *QS World University Rankings* ranked the university 98th internationally and 4th in Germany.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In the 2024 Times Higher Education World University Rankings, the university is ranked 102nd internationally and 9th in Germany.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Because of an unresolved dispute over the counting of Nobel laureates before the Second World War (both Humboldt and Free University of Berlin claim to be the rightful successor of the University of Berlin), both do not appear in the *Academic Ranking of World Universities* (*ARWU*) anymore.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The last *ARWU*, placed the FU at 83rd in the world in 2007.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In the 2023 QS Subject Ranking, Free University of Berlin ranks first in Germany in English, modern languages, politics, and sociology.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In the 2023 THE Subject Ranking, Free University of Berlin ranks first in Germany in the social sciences.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In the 2022 ARWU Subject Ranking, Free University of Berlin ranks first in Germany in human biological sciences and pharmacy, while sharing the first place in biomedical engineering, law, and nursing.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] News & World Report* listed Free University of Berlin as the 111th best in the world, climbing five positions.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Being among the 100 best in the world in 18 areas of 28 ranked.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In the German "ExcellenceRanking" of the CHE (*Center for Higher Education Development*) in 2013, Free University of Berlin ranks top in the fields of Biology, Chemistry, Physics and Political science.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In the CHE "SubjectRanking", Freie Universität has been evaluated as one of Germany's best universities in Earth sciences, Computer science and Philosophy and also ranks among the Top 5 in Psychology, English studies and Education.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Free University of Berlin maintains wide-ranging international contacts with top universities and organizations, which provide key impulses for research and teaching.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The university is a founding member of the global educational center for the study of transnational law, the Centre for Transnational Legal Studies in London.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] First contacts with universities in Eastern Europe were made in the 1970s.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The newly established Centre for International Cooperation (CIC) concentrates on identifying new strategic partners for international projects.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Today, Free University of Berlin has established over 400 partnerships in five continents, many of them as part of the European ERASMUS program.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Every year, about 600 visiting scientists contribute to the university teaching and research.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] For the grant programs in Germany, the Free University of Berlin is one of the first choices both for the ERASMUS and Tempus as well as for the Fulbright program and the international programs of the German Academic Exchange Service (DAAD).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] An International Summer and Winter University (FUBiS) has been set up for international students offering (semi-)intensive German courses and numerous subject courses.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The Free University of Berlin operates foreign branch offices in New York City, Brussels, Moscow, Beijing, Cairo, São Paulo, and New Delhi.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The foreign branch offices work to expand upon cooperation partnerships already existing with universities in the country.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In April 2005, the Free University of Berlin, in conjunction with LMU Munich, opened a joint representative office in New York.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] This German University Alliance, located in German House, the seat of the German Consulate General and the German UN Mission, represents the interests of the two universities in the United States and Canada and works to increase the exchange of students and scientists.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In addition, the Free University of Berlin, as the first German institution of higher education, founded an alumni and fundraising organization, the Friends of the Freie Universität Berlin (FFUB) in New York.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Since 2003 this organization has maintained close contact with alumni and scientists of the Free University of Berlin in the U.S. and attempts to gain alumni and friends as sponsors, to strengthen the long-lasting trans-Atlantic relations.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Some of the proceeds from these fundraising activities were contributed to the renovation of the Henry Ford Building.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] In April 2006 Peking University opened its first branch in Germany.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Its objectives include the promotion of knowledge of Chinese culture, the cultivation of Chinese-German cooperation, and the spread of the Chinese language.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Duke University in Durham, North Carolina, has a Berlin program (Duke in Berlin) that is held in cooperation with the Free University of Berlin and Humboldt University.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The University of California System organizes programs for American students in Berlin and Potsdam.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The UC System maintains an office at the Free University of Berlin to attend to the needs of exchange students from the California campuses.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] The Office of Global Programs of Columbia University in New York administers the Berlin Consortium for German Studies.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] This temporary enrollment is preceded by a six-week intensive language program.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/free-university-of-berlin] Alumni of the Free University of Berlin include several scientists, philosophers and politicians, amongst them five Nobel Prize winners and 15 Leibniz laureates.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Language documentation seeks to create as thorough a record as possible of the speech community for both posterity and language revitalization.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] This record can be public or private depending on the needs of the community and the purpose of the documentation.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] In practice, language documentation can range from solo linguistic anthropological fieldwork to the creation of vast online archives that contain dozens of different languages, such as FirstVoices or OLAC.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Language documentation provides a firmer foundation for linguistic analysis in that it creates a corpus of materials in the language.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] The materials in question can range from vocabulary lists and grammar rules to children's books and translated works.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] These materials can then support claims about the structure of the language and its usage.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] This should be seen as a basic taxonomic task for linguistics, identifying the range of languages and their characteristics.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] While various linguists had already been practising language documentation during the 20th century, the discipline was established as a specific field within linguistics following a 1998 publication by Nikolaus Himmelmann, which many understand as foundational.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Typical steps involve recording, maintaining metadata, transcribing (often using the International Phonetic Alphabet and/or a "practical orthography" made up for that language), annotation and analysis, translation into a language of wider communication, archiving and dissemination.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Critical is the creation of good records in the course of doing language description.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] The materials can be archived, but not all archives are equally adept at handling language materials preserved in varying technological formats, and not all are equally accessible to potential users.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Language documentation complements language description, which aims to describe a language's abstract system of structures and rules in the form of a grammar or dictionary.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] By practising good documentation in the form of recordings with transcripts and then collections of texts and a dictionary, a linguist works better and can provide materials for use by speakers of the language.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] New technologies permit better recordings with better descriptions which can be housed in digital archives such as AILLA, Pangloss, or Paradisec.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] These resources can then be made available to the speakers.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] The first example of a grammar with a media corpus is Thieberger's grammar of South Efate (2006).
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Language documentation has also given birth to new specialized publications, such as the free online and peer-reviewed journal *Language Documentation & Conservation* and the SOAS working papers *Language Documentation & Description*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] The digitization of archives is a critical component of language documentation and revitalization projects.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] There are descriptive records of local languages that could be put to use in language revitalization projects that are overlooked due to obsolete formatting, incomplete hard-copy records, or systematic inaccessibility.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Local archives in particular, which may have vital records of the area's indigenous languages, are chronically underfunded and understaffed.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Historic records relating to language that have been collected by non-linguists such as missionaries can be overlooked if the collection is not digitized.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Physical archives are naturally more vulnerable to damage and information loss.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Language documentation can be beneficial to individuals who would like to teach or learn an endangered language.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] If a language has limited documentation this also limits how it can be used in a language revitalization context.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Teaching with documentation and linguist's field notes can provide more context for those teaching the language and can add information they were not aware of.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Documentation can be useful for understanding culture and heritage, as well as learning the language.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Important components when teaching a language includes: Listening, reading, speaking, writing, and cultural components.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Documentation gives resources to further the skills for learning a language.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] For example, the Kaurna language was revitalized through written resources.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] These written documents served as the only resource and were used to re-introduce the language and one way was through teaching, which also included the making of a teaching guide for the Kaurna language.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/language-documentation] Language documentation and teaching have a relationship because if there are no fluent speakers of a language, documentation can be used as a teaching resource.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/mandana-seyfeddinipur] She studied linguistics and Persian studies at the Free University of Berlin and graduated with a Master's degree.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/mandana-seyfeddinipur] She received her doctorate at the Max Planck Institute for Psycholinguistics at Radboud University Nijmegen from 2000 to 2005.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/mandana-seyfeddinipur] Her dissertation was entitled *Disfluency: Interrupting speech and gesture*.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/mandana-seyfeddinipur] She then worked as a Marie Curie postdoctoral work Stanford University from 2006 to 2009.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/mandana-seyfeddinipur] Since 2014 she has headed the Endangered Languages Archive (ELAR), which deals with the digital preservation of endangered languages and makes digital collections of endangered languages digitally accessible worldwide.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/mandana-seyfeddinipur] Seyfeddinipur moved with the Endangered Languages Documentation Programme to the Berlin-Brandenburg Academy in 2021.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/mandana-seyfeddinipur] Seyfeddinipur teaches courses in Visual Mode of Language, the use of videos in field research on endangered languages, language psychology and language use.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/mandana-seyfeddinipur] Her research interests focus on (audiovisual) language documentation, cultural and linguistic diversity in language use, psycholinguistics and language production.
[src:mandana-seyfeddinipur/mandana-seyfeddinipur] She is also involved in work on the preservation of poetry and other literature in endangered languages.
